SIMPLE: prison
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prison
<hw>Pris"on</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>prehensio</ets>, <ets>prensio</ets>, a seizing, arresting, fr.
<ets>prehendre</ets>, <ets>prendere</ets>, to lay hold of, to seize. See
<er>Prehensile</er>, and cf. <er>Prize</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
<er>Misprision</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place where persons are
confined, or restrained of personal liberty; hence, a place or state
o<?/ confinement, restraint, or safe custody.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bring my soul out of <qex>prison</qex>, that I may praise thy
name.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cxlii. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The tyrant Aeolus, . . . ⟦br⟧
With power imperial, curbs the struggling winds,⟦br⟧
And sounding tempests in dark <qex>prisons</qex> binds.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically, a building for the safe custody or
confinement of criminals and others committed by lawful
authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Prison bars</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Prison
base</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See <er>Base</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 24.</cd> --
<col><b>Prison breach</b></col>. <fld>(Law)</fld> <cd>See Note under 3d
<er>Escape</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 4.</cd> -- <col><b>Prison
house</b></col>, <cd>a prison.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Prison
ship</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a ship fitted up for the
confinement of prisoners.</cd> -- <col><b>Prison van</b></col>, <cd>a
carriage in which prisoners are conveyed to and from
prison.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prison</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prison
<hw>Pris"on</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Prisoned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Prisoning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To imprison; to
shut up in, or as in, a prison; to confine; to restrain from
liberty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>prisoned</qex> eagle dies for rage.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His true respect will <qex>prison</qex> false desire.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bind (together); to enchain.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sir William Crispyn with the duke was led⟦br⟧
Together <qex>prisoned</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Robert of
Brunne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prisoner</ent>⟦br⟧
